description.narrative:
This contribution relates to the second phase of the Strategic Partnership for Oxfam Novib's Theory of Change (ToC) Conflict and Fragility. It covers the last two years of the Strategic Partnership: 2019 and 2020.
Progress on reducing conflict and fragility at national level often depends on the effective translation of international principles and support that can make a difference in the specific political context. Therefore, the Conflict and Fragility (C<(>&<)>F) ToC focuses especially on #what works# when it comes toimplementing international standards or frameworks on the ground: the UN resolution 1325 Women, Peace and Security with a focus on inclusive peacebuilding and inclusive security and the application of international standards about transparency, accountability andconflict sensitivity to companies in a (post) conflict situations.
At the start of the second phase, the global context has not changed for the better in the sense that we are still witnessing a series of protracted crises in which formal peace processes struggle to get started (e.g. Afghanistan), fail to reach an agreement (e.g. Yemen) or where peace deals still need to be implemented (e.g.South Sudan). In Myanmar, the military operations launched in August 2017 in Rakhine continue to reverberate both in Myanmar, as well as across the border.
While protracted crises demand more international attention and advocacy, there is a global tendency towards more nationalist, inward looking and populist agendas. This is also affecting public and political debates, for example, about conflict related issues such as the need to step up humanitarian assistance and support for refugees and the internally displaced.
Inthis context, the process of co-creation with partners in countries for the remainder of the project has resulted in a renewed ambition to jointly define focus areas for influencing. In the previous three years, support was especially focused on general influencing skills and national influencing strategy development. This was useful but did not work enough towards the Worldwide Influencing Network (WIN) ambition of connecting influencing efforts at various levels. This shift involves stepping up efforts to connect issues, share experiences, and learn from each other#s insights and the contextual developments of country projects. Linking can take the form of jointly influencing international targets such as African Union, UN and Regional Economic Communities; but it can also take place thematically, by linking the work in three countries on Women, Peace and Security (Occupied Palestinian Territory and Israel (OPTI), Yemen and Afghanistan), connecting the experience of South Sudan to Niger in terms of inclusive security, and linking Myanmar#s and Nigeria#s private sectorinfluencing work to Oxfam#s international campaign capacity.

participating-org.narrative: Oxfam Novib was founded in 1956 as the Netherlands Organisation for International Assistance (Novib), and joined forces with Oxfam in 1994. Oxfam Novib is member of the Oxfam International confederation. Working together in the confederation, the Oxfam affiliates can speak with one clear and compelling voice on issues of global concern: climate change, health and education for all, agriculture, trade, and conflicts and emergencies. Oxfam Novib's main office is based in The Netherlands, it supports the work of a network of local offices, the implementation of global projects, fundraising, campaigning and advocacy. Oxfam Novib’s the Hague office contributes towards this project’s implementation.
